and market conditions to inform business decisions. It provides insights into market trends, customer preferences, and competitive dynamics. This process can be based on primary or secondary data and is used to assess the potential success of new product launches. By understanding consumers' needs and preferences, companies can make informed decisions about product development and marketing strategies. Market Research serves as an external source of valuable information that helps businesses navigate the competitive landscape effectively.\n3. SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS, Sensitivity analysis calculates how responsive a decision is to changes in any of the variables used to calculate it.\nRelationships\n\nid,source,target,description\n10,FOCUS GROUP,MARKET RESEARCH,Focus group is related to market research. They are both research techniques to deal with uncertainty.\n11,MARKET RESEARCH,FOCUS GROUP,Market research is related to focus group. They are both research techniques to deal with uncertainty.\n\nOutput:\n{{\n    \"title\": \"Chapter 8: Risk and Uncertainty\",\n    \"summary\": \"Chapter 8 covers the following Learning Outcomes. C. Decision-Making Techniques 6. Dealing with risk and uncertainty in decision making a) Suggest research techniques to reduce uncertainty (e.g. focus groups, market research). b) Explain the use of simulation, expected values and sensitivity. c) Apply expected values and sensitivity to decision-making problems. d) Apply the techniques of maximax, maximin and minimax regret to decision-making problems, including the production of profit tables. e) Interpret a decision tree and use it to solve a multi-stage decision problem. f) Calculate the value of perfect and imperfect information. \",\n    \"rating\": 7.0,\n    \"rating_explanation\": \"The impact severity rating is high due to the fundamental importance of bookkeeping in accounting.\",\n    \"findings\": [\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Focus groups and market research are important research techniques to reduce uncertainty\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Companies often use focus groups and/or market research to deal with uncertainty. Focus groups are used to reduce uncertainty about new products by gathering opinions from a group of people in an interactive environment. Participants are chosen at random and may be observed by marketing professionals. Market Research involves the systematic gathering and analyzing of data about consumers, competitors, and market conditions to inform business decisions. It provides insights into market trends, customer preferences, and competitive dynamics. This process can be based on primary or secondary data and is used to assess the potential success of new product launches. By understanding consumers' needs and preferences, companies can make informed decisions about product development and marketing strategies. Market Research serves as an external source of valuable information that helps businesses navigate the competitive landscape effectively. [Data: Concepts (1, 2); Relationships (10, 11)]\"\n        }},\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Explain and apply sensitivity analysis to decision-making problems\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Sensitivity analysis calculates how responsive a decision is to changes in any of the variables used in making that decision. It looks at one variable at a time and measures how much the variable can change by (in percentage terms) before affecting the decision. The smaller the percentage, the more sensitive the decision is to that variable. Sensitivity % = Profit/Variable  [Data: Concepts (3)]\"\n        }}\n    ]\n}}\n\n# Real Data\n\nUse the following text for your answer. Do not make anything up in your answer.\n\nText:\n-----Entities-----\nhuman_readable_id,title,description,degree\n1315,\"\"\"DIVISION A\"\"\",\"Division A is a part of Bath Co that purchases fittings from Division B and has the potential to buy fittings externally for $65 per set if given autonomy. Additionally, Division A is the adaptor division of Portable Garage Co, producing adaptors used to charge mobile devices and laptops.\",10\n1978,\"\"\"DIVISION B\"\"\",\"Division B is a part of Bath Co that manufactures and sells fittings both internally to Division A and externally. It does not save costs by supplying internally. Additionally, Division B is the battery division of Portable Garage Co, producing portable battery chargers that can also charge mobile devices and laptops.\",9\n1996,\"\"\"INTERNAL SALES\"\"\",\"\"\"Internal sales refer to transactions between divisions within the same company. Division B buys adaptors from Division A.\"\"\",5\n1980,\"\"\"OPTIMIZED TRANSFER PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"Optimized transfer pricing refers to setting transfer prices in a way that maximizes the overall profit of the company while considering the autonomy and motivation of divisional managers.\"\"\",3\n1988,\"\"\"EXTERNAL SALES\"\"\",\"\"\"External sales\"\" refer to transactions with customers outside the company. Specifically, for Division M of Mobe Co., external sales are made to customers outside of Mobe Co. The selling price per unit for these sales is $850, with variable costs of $770 per unit. Additionally, Division A engages in external sales by selling adaptors to other companies, while also selling internally to Division B.\",3\n935,\"\"\"FIXED OVERHEADS\"\"\",\"\"\"Fixed overheads\"\" are the fixed costs that do not change with the level of production. They are largely independent of changes in activity and remain constant over wide ranges in the short term, making a fixed overhead rate per unit of activity inappropriate for control purposes. Division B has annual fixed overheads of $5,460,000, while Division A has annual fixed overheads of $2,200,000.\",3\n1979,\"\"\"PROFIT STATEMENT\"\"\",\"\"\"A profit statement is a financial document that shows the revenue, costs, and profit for each division and the company as a whole. It includes external sales, inter-divisional transfers, variable costs, and fixed costs.\"\"\",2\n1993,\"\"\"OPTIMIZING ADAPTOR SUPPLY FOR PORTABLE GARAGE CO (PGC)\"\"\",\"\"\"The Portable Garage Co (PGC) has two divisions: Division B (battery division) and Division A (adaptor division). Division B uses adaptors from Division A for its upgraded portable batteries, which can charge mobile devices and laptops. Division A also sells adaptors externally. The case involves optimizing the supply and pricing of adaptors between the divisions to maximize group profits.\"\"\",2\n1995,\"\"\"ADAPTOR\"\"\",\"\"\"An adaptor is a product sold by Division A, used to charge mobile devices and laptops by attaching them to a car's internal power source.\"\"\",1\n1998,\"\"\"CURRENT ANNUAL PRODUCTION CAPACITY\"\"\",\"\"\"Current annual production capacity is the maximum number of units that can be produced in a year. Division A's current annual production capacity for adaptors is 350,000 units.\"\"\",1\n1306,\"\"\"PERFORMANCE MEASUREMENT OF DIVISIONS\"\"\",\"\"\"The quiz question asks which of the following statements is correct in relation to measuring the performance of both divisions: Both methods will favour Division A, Both methods will favour Division B, ROI will favour Division A, RI will favour Division B, RI will favour Division A, ROI will favour Division B. The correct answer is A.\"\"\",1\n1994,\"\"\"PORTABLE BATTERY\"\"\",\"\"\"A portable battery is a product sold by Division B that can start a car's engine and charge mobile devices and laptops.\"\"\",1\n1997,\"\"\"MAXIMUM ANNUAL MARKET DEMAND\"\"\",\"\"\"Maximum annual market demand is the highest number of units that can be sold in a year. Division B's maximum annual market demand for portable batteries is 180,000 units.\"\"\",1\n930,\"\"\"INFORMATION USED FOR SETTING STANDARDS\"\"\",\"\"\"Information used for setting standards includes price per unit of input and quantity used per unit of output, determined through various methods such as market prices, bills of materials, time and motion studies, and wage rates.\"\"\",6\n1199,\"\"\"FULL COST PLUS METHOD\"\"\",\"The \"\"FULL COST PLUS METHOD\"\" sets transfer prices by adding a markup to the full cost of production. This method ensures that the supplying division covers its production costs. However, it may lead to dysfunctional decisions if there is spare capacity. Under this method, the supplying division charges the full absorption cost plus a markup. To avoid transferring inefficiencies from the selling division to the buying division, standard costs should be used rather than actual costs.\",4\n1985,\"\"\"OPTIMIZING TRANSFER PRICING FOR MOBE CO'S ELECTRONIC MOTORS\"\"\",\"\"\"Mobe Co manufactures electronic mobility scooters and is split into two divisions: the scooter division (Division S) and the motor division (Division M). Division M supplies electronic motors to both Division S and external customers. The case discusses the optimal transfer pricing strategy to maximize overall company profit while maintaining divisional autonomy.\"\"\",4\n1987,\"\"\"DIVISION M\"\"\",\"\"\"Division M is the motor division of Mobe Co, with the capacity to produce 60,000 electronic motors per year. It sells motors both to Division S and to external customers, with a selling price of $850 per unit for external sales and variable costs of $770 per unit.\"\"\",4\n1989,\"\"\"SPARE CAPACITY\"\"\",\"\"\"Spare capacity\"\" refers to the unused production capacity that can be utilized without incurring additional fixed costs. Division M has spare capacity to produce 28,000 motors. This spare capacity is the unused production capacity of Division M, which is 25,000 units per year after meeting the maximum external demand of 35,000 units.\",3\n136,\"\"\"DIRECT LABOUR HOURS\"\"\",\"\"\"Direct labour hours\"\" are determined through time and motion studies to establish the most efficient production method and standard hours for job completion. Additionally, direct labour hours serve as a basis used in both re-apportionment and absorption to allocate costs based on the number of hours worked by direct labour.\",1\n1208,\"\"\"EXAMPLE OF COST-BASED APPROACHES\"\"\",\"\"\"An example of cost-based approaches involves a division (A) transferring its production to another division (B). The example illustrates the impact of using variable cost, full cost, and full cost plus methods on divisional and group profits.\"\"\",3\n931,\"\"\"PRICE PER UNIT OF INPUT\"\"\",\"\"\"The price per unit of input is usually set to reflect current market prices for the budgeted period, with adjustments made for external factors.\"\"\",1\n932,\"\"\"QUANTITY OF MATERIALS\"\"\",\"\"\"Quantities of materials are determined by a bill of materials prepared by product design, engineering, or a works foreman, with allowances for expected levels of waste.\"\"\",1\n933,\"\"\"WAGE RATES\"\"\",\"\"\"Wage rates are determined by company policy or negotiations between management and unions, sometimes set before annual wage negotiations are concluded.\"\"\",1\n934,\"\"\"VARIABLE OVERHEADS\"\"\",\"\"\"Variable overheads are calculated as a rate per unit of activity, usually direct labour hours or machine hours, based on past data if no direct relationship between resources and output is observable.\"\"\",1\n1986,\"\"\"DIVISION S\"\"\",\"\"\"Division S is the scooter division of Mobe Co, which requires 35,000 electronic motors for the coming year. It has the option to buy these motors either from Division M or from an external supplier at $800 each.\"\"\",2\n1992,\"\"\"ETHICAL TRANSFER PRICING SYSTEM\"\"\",\"\"\"An ethical transfer pricing system ensures decisions are in the best interest of the organization, gives divisional managers autonomy, and allows fair measurement of divisional performance.\"\"\",1\n1201,\"\"\"MARGINAL COST METHOD\"\"\",\"\"\"Marginal cost method sets the transfer price at the variable cost plus any incremental fixed costs, such as stepped costs.\"\"\",3\n1204,\"\"\"ADVANTAGES OF FULL COST PLUS METHOD\"\"\",\"\"\"The full cost plus method is easy to calculate if a standard costing system exists, covers all costs of the selling division, and may approximate to market price.\"\"\",1\n1205,\"\"\"DISADVANTAGES OF FULL COST PLUS METHOD\"\"\",\"\"\"The full cost plus method can lead to dysfunctional decisions as the fixed costs of the selling division become the variable costs of the buying division, and the markup is arbitrary.\"\"\",1\n1206,\"\"\"ADVANTAGES OF MARGINAL COST METHOD\"\"\",\"\"\"The marginal cost method is optimal for goal congruence when the selling division has spare capacity or no external market exists.\"\"\",1\n1207,\"\"\"DISADVANTAGES OF MARGINAL COST METHOD\"\"\",\"\"\"The marginal cost method may be difficult to calculate as variable cost is often used as an approximation.\"\"\",1\n1981,\"\"\"ENCOURAGING DIVISIONAL MANAGERS\"\"\",\"\"\"Encouraging divisional managers involves creating policies and incentives that align the decisions of divisional managers with the overall interests of the company, especially in the context of transfer pricing.\"\"\",1\n1200,\"\"\"VARIABLE COST PLUS METHOD\"\"\",\"\"\"Variable cost plus is similar to full cost plus, where the transfer price is set at the variable cost plus a mark-up.\"\"\",1\n\n\n-----Relationships-----\nhuman_readable_id,source,target,description,rank\n242,\"\"\"VARIABLE COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"DIVISION A\"\"\",\"\"\"Division A has variable costs.\"\"\",19\n241,\"\"\"VARIABLE COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"DIVISION B\"\"\",\"\"\"Division B has variable costs.\"\"\",18\n1295,\"\"\"DIVISION A\"\"\",\"\"\"INTERNAL SALES\"\"\",\"\"\"Division A sells adaptors to Division B through internal sales.\"\"\",15\n1189,\"\"\"TRANSFER PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"DIVISION B\"\"\",\"\"\"Transfer pricing affects Division B as it determines the revenue Division B earns from selling fittings to Division A.\"\"\",15\n1779,\"\"\"DIVISION B\"\"\",\"\"\"INTERNAL SALES\"\"\",\"\"\"Division B buys adaptors from Division A through internal sales.\"\"\",14\n1292,\"\"\"DIVISION A\"\"\",\"\"\"OPTIMIZED TRANSFER PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"Optimized transfer pricing allows Division A to purchase fittings externally, potentially increasing its profit.\"\"\",13\n1296,\"\"\"DIVISION A\"\"\",\"\"\"EXTERNAL SALES\"\"\",\"\"\"Division A sells adaptors externally.\"\"\",13\n847,\"\"\"FIXED OVERHEADS\"\"\",\"\"\"DIVISION A\"\"\",\"\"\"Division A has fixed overheads.\"\"\",13\n1291,\"\"\"DIVISION A\"\"\",\"\"\"PROFIT STATEMENT\"\"\",\"\"\"The profit statement includes the revenue, costs, and profit for Division A.\"\"\",12\n1293,\"\"\"DIVISION A\"\"\",\"\"\"OPTIMIZING ADAPTOR SUPPLY FOR PORTABLE GARAGE CO (PGC)\"\"\",\"\"\"The case involves Division A of Portable Garage Co.\"\"\",12\n1776,\"\"\"DIVISION B\"\"\",\"\"\"OPTIMIZED TRANSFER PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"Optimized transfer pricing allows Division B to prioritize external customers, potentially increasing its profit.\"\"\",12\n846,\"\"\"FIXED OVERHEADS\"\"\",\"\"\"DIVISION B\"\"\",\"\"\"Division B has fixed overheads.\"\"\",12\n1294,\"\"\"DIVISION A\"\"\",\"\"\"ADAPTOR\"\"\",\"\"\"Division A produces adaptors.\"\"\",11\n1297,\"\"\"DIVISION A\"\"\",\"\"\"CURRENT ANNUAL PRODUCTION CAPACITY\"\"\",\"\"\"Division A has a current annual production capacity for adaptors.\"\"\",11\n1285,\"\"\"PERFORMANCE MEASUREMENT OF DIVISIONS\"\"\",\"\"\"DIVISION A\"\"\",\"\"\"Both methods (RI and ROI) will favour Division A because performance for Division A will be assessed on a lower value for assets due to higher accumulated depreciation.\"\"\",11\n1775,\"\"\"DIVISION B\"\"\",\"\"\"PROFIT STATEMENT\"\"\",\"\"\"The profit statement includes the revenue, costs, and profit for Division B.\"\"\",11\n1777,\"\"\"DIVISION B\"\"\",\"\"\"OPTIMIZING ADAPTOR SUPPLY FOR PORTABLE GARAGE CO (PGC)\"\"\",\"\"\"The case involves Division B of Portable Garage Co.\"\"\",11\n1778,\"\"\"DIVISION B\"\"\",\"\"\"PORTABLE BATTERY\"\"\",\"\"\"Division B produces portable batteries.\"\"\",10\n1780,\"\"\"DIVISION B\"\"\",\"\"\"MAXIMUM ANNUAL MARKET DEMAND\"\"\",\"\"\"Division B has a maximum annual market demand for portable batteries.\"\"\",10\n845,\"\"\"INFORMATION USED FOR SETTING STANDARDS\"\"\",\"\"\"FIXED OVERHEADS\"\"\",\"\"\"Information used for setting standards includes determining fixed overheads.\"\"\",9\n1199,\"\"\"FULL COST PLUS METHOD\"\"\",\"\"\"INTERNAL SALES\"\"\",\"\"\"The full cost plus method is used to set transfer prices for internal sales.\"\"\",9\n1783,\"\"\"OPTIMIZING TRANSFER PRICING FOR MOBE CO'S ELECTRONIC MOTORS\"\"\",\"\"\"DIVISION M\"\"\",\"\"\"The case of Optimizing Transfer Pricing for Mobe Co's Electronic Motors involves Division M, which has the capacity to produce 60,000 electronic motors per year.\"\"\",8\n1789,\"\"\"SPARE CAPACITY\"\"\",\"\"\"INTERNAL SALES\"\"\",\"\"\"Spare capacity affects the number of units Division M can sell internally.\"\"\",8\n139,\"\"\"DIRECT LABOUR HOURS\"\"\",\"\"\"INFORMATION USED FOR SETTING STANDARDS\"\"\",\"\"\"Information used for setting standards includes determining direct labour hours.\"\"\",7\n1787,\"\"\"DIVISION M\"\"\",\"\"\"EXTERNAL SALES\"\"\",\"\"\"Division M sells motors both to Division S and to external customers, with a selling price of $850 per unit for external sales.\"\"\",7\n1788,\"\"\"DIVISION M\"\"\",\"\"\"SPARE CAPACITY\"\"\",\"\"\"Division M has a spare capacity of 25,000 units per year after meeting the maximum external demand of 35,000 units.\"\"\",7\n1198,\"\"\"FULL COST PLUS METHOD\"\"\",\"\"\"EXAMPLE OF COST-BASED APPROACHES\"\"\",\"\"\"The Example of Cost-based Approaches includes the Full Cost Plus Method.\"\"\",7\n1784,\"\"\"OPTIMIZING TRANSFER PRICING FOR MOBE CO'S ELECTRONIC MOTORS\"\"\",\"\"\"EXTERNAL SALES\"\"\",\"\"\"The case of Optimizing Transfer Pricing for Mobe Co's Electronic Motors discusses the external sales made by Division M, which has a maximum external demand of 35,000 units per year.\"\"\",7\n841,\"\"\"INFORMATION 